[[File:Natyra jonë.jpg|230px|thumb|right|The [[Valbonë Valley National Park]] in northern [[Albania]].]]

The '''Environment of [[Albania]]''' is characterised by unique flora and fauna and a variety of landforms contained within a small nation. It also consists of different [[ecoregions]], which represent the natural [[Geography of Albania|geographical]] [[ecosystem]], water systems, [[weather]], [[renewable resources]] and influences upon them.

Of the factors caused by human intervention that can affect this [[environment (biophysical)|environment]], activities that sustain the [[economy of Albania]] such as [[mining]] and [[forestry]] are notably influential. The environment strongly influences public health in Albania, as for example [[air pollution]] and [[smog]] in [[urban area]]s such as in [[Tirana]] can result in great distress for those with [[Respiration (physiology)|respiratory]] conditions such as [[asthma]].

== Geography ==
{{Hatnote|[[File:commons-logo.svg|12px|link=|alt=]] Main article: [[Geography of Albania]]; See also: [[commons:Atlas of Albania|Atlas of Albania]] at [[Wikimedia Commons]]}} 

[[Albania]] is a small predominantly mountainous country between [[Southeastern Europe|Southeastern]] and [[Southern Europe]], on facing the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] and [[Ionian
n Sea|Ionian sea]]s within the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. It has a total area of {{convert|28748|km2|0|abbr=off}}, bordering [[Montenegro]] to the northwest, [[Kosovo]] to the northeast, [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] to the east and [[Greece]] to the south.<ref>{{cite web|title=Albania country profile|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-17679574|website=bbc.com|location=Europe|language=English|date=19 June 2017|quote=Albania is a small, mountainous country in the Balkan peninsula, with a long Adriatic and Ionian coastline.}}</ref> It lies between latitudes [[42nd parallel north|42°]] and [[39th parallel north|39° N]] and between longitudes [[21st meridian east|21°]] and [[19th meridian east|19° E]]. Its coastline length is {{convert|476|km|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="Albania pdf">{{cite web| author=Eftimi, R. |url=http://aguas.igme.es/igme/publica/tiac-02/ALBANIA-I.pdf|title=SOME CONSIDERATIONS ON SEAWATER-FRESHWATER RELATIONSHIP IN ALBANIAN COASTAL AREA|publisher=ITA Consult}}</ref>{{rp|240}} and extends along the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] and [[Ionian Sea]]s.

== Climate ==
{{Hatnote|[[File:commons-logo.svg|12px|link=|alt=]] Main article: [[Climate of Albania]]; See also: [[commons:Category:Climate of Albania|Climate of Albania]] at [[Wikimedia Commons]]}}

With Albania's coastline facing the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] and [[Ionian Sea|Ionian sea]]s, its highlands backed upon the elevated Balkan landmass, and the entire country lying at a latitude subject to a variety of weather patterns during the winter and summer seasons, [[Albania]] has a high number of climatic regions for such a small area. The coastal lowlands have typically mediterranean climate; the highlands have a continental climate. In both the lowlands and the interior, the weather varies markedly from north to south.

Inland temperatures are affected more by differences in elevation than by latitude or any other factor. Low winter temperatures in the mountains are caused by the continental air mass that dominates the weather in Eastern Europe and the Balkans. Northerly and northeasterly winds blow much of the time. Average summer temperatures are lower than in the coastal areas and much lower at higher elevations, but daily fluctuations are greater. Daytime maximum temperatures in the interior basins and river valleys are very high, but the nights are almost always cool.

== Biodiversity ==
{{Main article|Biodiversity of Albania|Protected areas of Albania|l1=Biodiversity}} 
{{Hatnote|[[File:commons-logo.svg|12px|link=|alt=]] See also: [[commons:Category:Biodiversity of Albania|Biodiversity of Albania]] and [[commons:Category:Protected areas of Albania|Protected areas of Albania]] at [[Wikimedia Commons]]}}

[[File:Butrint Panorama.jpg|230px|thumb|right|[[Butrint National Park]], a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]]]

[[Phytogeographically]], Albania is part of the [[Boreal Kingdom]] specifically, part of the [[Illyrian Provinces|Illyrian]] province of the [[Circumboreal Region]] and [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean region]] within the [[Boreal Kingdom|Boreal kingdom]]. Albania is divided into three ecoregions including [[Illyrian deciduous forests]], [[Dinaric Mountains mixed forests|Dinaric mixed forests]], [[Balkan mixed forests]] and [[Pindus Mountains mixed forests|Pindus mixed forests]]. Further, [[Biome]]s in Albania include [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest]] and [[Mediterranean forests, woodlands, and scrub]], that are all in the [[Palearctic ecozone]]. Due to its climatic, hydrological, geological and topographical conditions, Albania is one of the richest in Europe in terms of [[Biodiversity of Albania|biodiversity]]. Almost 30% of the entire flora and 42% fauna in the entire European contitent can be found in Albania.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biodiversity Albania|url=https://www.climatechangepost.com/albania/biodiversity/|website=climatechangepost.com|language=English|quote=Some of the 30% of the European plant species, and 42% of the European mammals can be found in the country. Albania's variety of wetlands, lagoons and large lakes also provide critical winter habitat for migratory birds (1).}}</ref>

There are 799 [[Protected areas of Albania|Albanian protected areas]], which covers a surface of {{convert|4600|km2|hectare}}. These include 15 [[National Parks of Albania|national park]]s, 5 protected landscape areas, 29 [[Strict Nature Reserve/Wilderness Area|nature reserves]], 4 protected resource areas and 750 [[Natural monument|nature monument]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biodiversity and Protected Areas-- Albania|url=http://www.catsg.org/balkanlynx/04_land-use/4_3_protected-area/protected-areas/Pdfs/EarthTrends_2003_Protected_areas_in_Albania.pdf|website=catsg.org|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Albania, Europe|url=https://www.protectedplanet.net/country/ALB|website=protectedplanet.net|language=English}}</ref> The national parks covering a surface area of {{convert|210668.48|hectare|km2|}} or roughly 13.65% of the overall territory.<ref>[http://www.mjedisi.gov.al/files/userfiles/Biodiversiteti/ZM&PK-Pershkrim.pdf Përshkrimi i Rrjetit aktual të zonave të mbrojtura]</ref> The nation host also 8 archaeological parks covering a surface area of {{convert|1120|hectare|km2|}}. The largest national park in Albania is the [[Fir of Hotova National Park]], covering a surface area of {{convert|34361|hectare|km2|}} and having the largest area of [[Bulgarian fir|Bulgarian Fir]] in the [[Balkans]]. Other large national parks includes the [[Butrint National Park]], [[Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park]], [[Divjaka-Karavasta National Park]], [[Prespa National Park]], [[Shebenik-Jabllanice National Park]], and others.

