{{about||the sea nymph named Peitho|Oceanids|the asteroid|118 Peitho}}
[[File:Pompejanischer Maler um 25 v. Chr. 001.jpg|thumb|[[Pompeii]]an fresco of Peitho (left) taking [[Eros (god)|Eros]] to [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]] and Anteros, circa 25 BCE, [[Naples National Archaeological Museum|Naples National Museum]].]]
In [[Greek mythology]], '''Peitho''' ({{lang-grc|Πειθώ|Peithō|Persuasion}}) is the [[goddess]] who personifies [[persuasion]] and [[seduction]]. Her [[Roman mythology|Roman]] [[name]] is [[Suadela]] or Suada.

[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] reports that after the unification of [[Athens]], [[Theseus]] set up a cult of [[Aphrodite Pandemos]] and Peitho on the south slope of [[Acropolis of Athens]]. According to the same author, they had also a sanctuary and a cult at [[Sicyon]]. In her role as an attendant or companion of Aphrodite, Peitho was intimately connected to the goddess of love and beauty. Ancient artists and poets explored this connection in their works. The connection is even deeper in the context of Ancient Greek marriage because a suitor had to negotiate with the father of a young woman for her hand in marriage and offer a bridal price in return for her. The most desirable women drew many prospective suitors, and persuasive skill often determined their success.

Aphrodite and Peitho were sometimes conflated to a certain extent, with the name Peitho appearing in conjunction with, or as an [[epithet]] of, Aphrodite's name. This helps to demonstrate how the relationship between persuasion and [[love]] (or desire) was important in Greek culture. Peitho's ancestry is somewhat unclear. According to [[Hesiod]] in the ''[[Theogony]]'', Peitho was the daughter of the Titans [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]] and [[Oceanus]],<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'', 346-349.</ref> which would make her an [[Oceanid]] and therefore sister of such notable goddesses as [[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]], [[Doris (mythology)|Doris]], and [[Metis (mythology)|Metis]]. However, Hesiod's classification of Peitho as an Oceanid is contradicted by other sources. 

When [[Zeus]] ordered the creation of the first woman, [[Pandora]], it was Peitho and the [[Charities]] who put golden necklaces around her neck, and the rich-haired Hours crowned Pandora's head with spring flowers.<ref>Hesiod, ''[[Works and Days]]'', 69-82.</ref> Peitho is identified as a member of the [[Charites]] by [[Hermesianax]],<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 9.35.1.</ref> and [[Nonnus]], in his ''[[Dionysiaca]]'', describes them as including Peitho, [[Pasithea]], and [[Aglaea|Aglaia]], all three of them daughters of [[Dionysus]] and Aphrodite.<ref>[[Nonnus]], ''[[Dionysiaca]]'', 24.261.</ref> She is most commonly considered a daughter of Aphrodite. Nonnus also lists Peitho as the wife of Hermes, the messenger of the gods.<ref>Nonnus, ''Dionysiaca'', 8.220.</ref><ref>Nonnus, ''Dionysiaca'', 48.230.</ref> However, in another source, Peitho is the first wife of [[Phoroneus]], and the mother of [[Aegialeus (King of Argos)|Aegialeus]] and [[Apis (Greek mythology)|Apia]]<ref>Scholiast on Euripides' Orestes 920.</ref>

